<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> <i><a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=rKFGit9aFssC&amp;printsec=frontcover#PRA1-PA29,M1" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=rKFGit9aFssC&amp;printsec=frontcover#PRA1-PA29,M1" rel="nofollow">The Tibetan book of the great liberation; or, The method of realizing nirvana through knowing the mind, preceded by an epitome of Padma-Sambhava’s biography and followed by Guru Phadampa Sangay’s teachings</a></i> According to English renderings by Sardar Bahädur S. W. Laden La and by the Lāmas Karma Sumdhon Paul, Lobzang Mingyur Dorje, and Kazi Dawa-Samdup. Introductions, annotations, and editing by W. Y. Evans-Wentz. With psychological commentary by <a href="/wiki/C._G._Jung" title="C. G. Jung" class="mw-redirect">C. G. Jung</a>. London, New York, Oxford University Press, 1954. (In the quotation, <i>Sangsara</i> is an alternate English representation of the term<i><a href="/wiki/Samsara" title="Samsara" class="mw-redirect">Samsara</a></i>.)</li>
